history.content:
Out of those classes, 126 and 127 are the most directly relevant to 189, but 127 might be a little overkill. 170 might also be helpful to prepare you for the mindset of taking math-y cs classes and to familiarize you with gradient descent, lp, etc.

If you haven't taken 70 yet, I'm not sure you can take any of these classes, however.

I don't have any experience with 104 or 113, but I didn't have them for 189, so I don't think they are necessary. If 126 is not being offered next semester, you could consider Stat 134 since you should have the prereqs for it, but I took it and would not recommend taking it unless you are intending on a stat major. Stat 140 also won't be offered next semester

Overall, I would probably recommend you take a linear algebra class instead such as 110 or ee16b if you are set on preparing for 189

children.subject:
In that case Math 104 or Stat 134 might be your best bet

Have you also considered CS 188? It might be difficult without the probability theory of cs70, so you might want to read some of the piazza threads on 188 and 70 concurrently
I've been told that 188 is somewhat redundant with 61B + 189, so I'm hesitant to take it.

188 and 189 have little overlap. It has a bit more in 61B, but only for the first couple of weeks.

188 only dabbles a bit in ML, and mostly does general / other AI techniques.

I probably should've included this in the question details, but I'm taking Math 110 right now, and doing pretty solid in it.

By the end of this semester I'll have taken Math 53 and 110, EE 16A and B, and CS 61 A and B

Math 104 and 113 will help almost not at all for 189 (they are cool, you should still take them if you have time!), 170 is useful to have a general overview of the field but less relevant than 126 and 127.
Why do you recommend taking stats 134 over EE 126?

You will probably struggle quite a bit in EE126 without the prereq of CS70.

This is less likely to be the case for Stats134.
Actually, my point was that it is better to take more probability before 189 rather than concurrently with it.  I cant comment on the relative difficulty of 134 vs. 126.
126 is more difficult. Definitely don't recommend taking it without 70 at least. Many students on the other hand take 134 before/together with 70 and do just fine.

As a TA for 189, I endorse the student answer above.  From personal experience, I would say Math 104 might help a tiiiny bit, but it's unnecessary, and 113 is pretty much completely unrelated.

One point of disagreement: I haven't taken EE 126, but if you're choosing between [taking no probability class other than 70, then taking 189 and 126 concurrently] and [taking 134 next semester to prepare for 189], I would consider the latter more seriously.  Many students who have only taken 70 struggle with the continuous probability in 189.

Of all these courses, consider EECS 127 as the most important. There are many many parallels between that course and 189. Then, if you have time take 126. The other courses are not really related but useful in their own right. Prof. Sahai has expressed that he would like all his students to take EECS 126 and 127 (@3644) even though he won't enforce that.
